{"id":"2006.03799","submitter":"Gergely Ambrus","authors":"Gergely Ambrus, Peter Nielsen, and Caledonia Wilson","title":"New estimates for convex layer numbers","comments":"Accepted for publication in Discrete Mathematics","journal-ref":"Discrete Mathematics 344 (2021), no. 7., 112424","doi":"10.1016/j.disc.2021.112424","report-no":null,"categories":"math.MG math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Starting with a finite point set $X \\subset \\mathbf{R}^d$, the peeling\nprocess repeatedly removes the set of the vertices of the convex hull of the\ncurrent set. The number of peeling steps required to completely remove $X$ is\ncalled the layer number of $X$, denoted by $L(X)$. In the article, we study the\nlayer number of evenly distributed families of point sets contained in $B^d$,\nthe $d$-dimensional unit ball. These sets consist of points in $B^d$ whose\nminimal distance is asymptotically as large as possible. We show that for a set\n$X$ belonging to an evenly distributed family, $L(X) \\geq \\Omega(|X|^{1/d})$\nholds, with the bound being asymptotically sharp. On the other hand, building\non earlier results, we prove that $L(X)\\leq O(|X|^{2/d})$ holds for $d\\geq 2$,\nwhich improves greatly on the current upper bound of $O(|X|^{(d+1)/2d})$ for $d\n\\geq 3$. Finally, we provide a recursive construction of evenly distributed\nfamilies whose sets satisfy $L(X) = \\Theta(|X|^{2/d - 1/(d 2^{d-1})})$, showing\nthat our upper bound is nearly tight.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Jun 2020 07:05:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 5 Nov 2020 09:34:06 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 22 Mar 2021 19:25:30 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 21 Apr 2021 09:10:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-04-22"}
